IBRARY FOR THE VISUALLY HANDICAPPED IN QUEBEC.     AN ACCOUNT OF AMERICA'S LARGEST FRENCH LANGUAGE LIBRARY OF BRAILLE BOOKS,SERVING 900 USERS, ATTACHED TO A MONTREAL INSTITUTE FOR THE VISUALLYHANDICAPPED. DESCRIBES THE ORIGIN AND DEVELOPMENT OF THE LIBRARY FROM ITSFOUNDATION IN 1861, AND GIVES DETAILS OF CURRENT HOLDINGS OF BOTH BRAILLE ANDTALKING BOOKS. THE FUNCTIONS OF THE STAFF AND VOLUNTARY HELPERS IN COLLECTIONMANAGEMENT ARE DESCRIBED, AND THE OPERATION OF THE POSTAL LOAN SYSTEMOUTLINED. PROCEDURES FOR SELECTING MATERIAL ARE DISCUSSED, AND THE ADVANTAGESOF TALKING BOOKS OVER BRAILLE DEBATED